WEBVTT

0
00:00:00.009 --> 00:00:02.269
Introduction to the stress cycle.

1
00:00:02.829 --> 00:00:05.329
Understanding what happens before behavior escalates.

2
00:00:06.260 --> 00:00:07.559
Let me ask you something.

3
00:00:07.860 --> 00:00:10.640
Have you ever been in a situation where everything seemed fine

4
00:00:11.020 --> 00:00:12.560
and then suddenly it wasn't?

5
00:00:12.859 --> 00:00:14.520
A young person reacts quickly,

6
00:00:14.739 --> 00:00:16.170
the situation escalates,

7
00:00:16.409 --> 00:00:18.639
and you're left trying to work out what just happened.

8
00:00:18.940 --> 00:00:21.440
You may have seen that more times than you can count.

9
00:00:21.780 --> 00:00:24.639
What's really going on here is something we call the stress cycle.

10
00:00:24.979 --> 00:00:25.299
Now,

11
00:00:25.500 --> 00:00:27.239
this is one of those concepts that

12
00:00:27.500 --> 00:00:28.649
once you understand it,

13
00:00:28.860 --> 00:00:30.799
changes how you see behavior completely

14
00:00:31.219 --> 00:00:33.200
because behavior doesn't just appear out of nowhere,

15
00:00:33.419 --> 00:00:34.860
there's always something leading up to it.

16
00:00:35.360 --> 00:00:38.180
The stress cycle starts before you see anything obvious.

17
00:00:38.360 --> 00:00:39.240
It might be a trigger,

18
00:00:39.360 --> 00:00:40.319
something small,

19
00:00:40.560 --> 00:00:41.599
a tone of voice,

20
00:00:41.840 --> 00:00:42.500
a look,

21
00:00:42.759 --> 00:00:44.020
a change in routine.

22
00:00:44.400 --> 00:00:45.759
It might not mean anything to you.

23
00:00:46.580 --> 00:00:47.639
But to the young person,

24
00:00:48.139 --> 00:00:48.830
it does.

25
00:00:49.259 --> 00:00:50.360
Then the body reacts.

26
00:00:50.619 --> 00:00:51.970
You might not see it straight away,

27
00:00:52.220 --> 00:00:53.919
but internally things are changing.

28
00:00:54.299 --> 00:00:55.680
Heart rate increases,

29
00:00:56.060 --> 00:00:56.970
breathing shifts,

30
00:00:57.139 --> 00:00:58.139
tension builds.

31
00:00:58.860 --> 00:01:01.020
They're moving towards that survival state,

32
00:01:01.360 --> 00:01:01.610
fight,

33
00:01:01.779 --> 00:01:01.970
flight,

34
00:01:01.979 --> 00:01:02.869
or freeze,

35
00:01:03.259 --> 00:01:05.220
and this is the point where we often miss it

36
00:01:05.699 --> 00:01:08.139
because outwardly it might still look manageable,

37
00:01:08.540 --> 00:01:10.639
but internally things are building.

38
00:01:11.059 --> 00:01:12.419
Then we reach escalation.

39
00:01:12.660 --> 00:01:14.680
This is where behavior becomes visible

40
00:01:14.940 --> 00:01:15.610
anger,

41
00:01:15.760 --> 00:01:16.680
refusal,

42
00:01:17.059 --> 00:01:18.089
walking away,

43
00:01:18.379 --> 00:01:19.180
shutting down.

44
00:01:19.980 --> 00:01:21.089
And here's the key point

45
00:01:21.750 --> 00:01:23.459
By the time you're seeing that behavior,

46
00:01:23.709 --> 00:01:24.769
the stress cycle

47
00:01:24.989 --> 00:01:26.349
is already well underway.

48
00:01:27.269 --> 00:01:29.589
So when we step in at that point and try to reason,

49
00:01:30.029 --> 00:01:30.220
question,

50
00:01:30.319 --> 00:01:31.230
or challenge,

51
00:01:31.629 --> 00:01:32.919
it often doesn't land

52
00:01:33.349 --> 00:01:36.139
because the thinking part of the brain isn't fully engaged.

53
00:01:36.430 --> 00:01:38.639
What this means in practice is simple

54
00:01:38.830 --> 00:01:40.029
but important.

55
00:01:40.470 --> 00:01:41.500
Timing matters.

56
00:01:41.870 --> 00:01:43.089
If we intervene early

57
00:01:43.230 --> 00:01:44.980
when we notice the small changes,

58
00:01:45.250 --> 00:01:46.940
we can often prevent escalation.

59
00:01:47.309 --> 00:01:48.470
If we miss that window,

60
00:01:48.629 --> 00:01:50.230
we need to shift our approach.

61
00:01:50.550 --> 00:01:51.389
At the peak,

62
00:01:51.589 --> 00:01:53.239
it's not about talking things through,

63
00:01:53.540 --> 00:01:54.769
it's about safety,

64
00:01:55.110 --> 00:01:55.870
calm tone.

65
00:01:56.330 --> 00:01:57.459
Clear presence

66
00:01:57.760 --> 00:01:58.720
giving space.

67
00:01:59.040 --> 00:02:00.360
Then after the peak,

68
00:02:00.599 --> 00:02:02.379
the young person starts to come down.

69
00:02:02.599 --> 00:02:03.910
You might see tiredness,

70
00:02:04.199 --> 00:02:05.089
withdrawal,

71
00:02:05.599 --> 00:02:07.379
sometimes even embarrassment or shame.

72
00:02:07.879 --> 00:02:09.850
This is where real work can happen,

73
00:02:10.220 --> 00:02:11.820
not in the heat of the moment,

74
00:02:12.160 --> 00:02:13.080
but afterwards.

75
00:02:13.479 --> 00:02:14.919
This is where reflection,

76
00:02:15.240 --> 00:02:15.960
repair,

77
00:02:16.160 --> 00:02:17.580
and learning take place.

78
00:02:17.839 --> 00:02:19.960
Now here's where it links directly to safeguarding.

79
00:02:20.270 --> 00:02:22.130
If we don't understand the stress cycle,

80
00:02:22.550 --> 00:02:24.149
we can misinterpret behavior.

81
00:02:24.350 --> 00:02:26.649
We might see defiance instead of distress,

82
00:02:27.029 --> 00:02:29.139
noncompliance instead of overwhelm,

83
00:02:29.470 --> 00:02:30.889
and that changes how we respond.

84
00:02:31.710 --> 00:02:33.429
From a trauma informed perspective,

85
00:02:33.789 --> 00:02:35.389
behavior is often communication.

86
00:02:36.130 --> 00:02:37.149
The stress cycle

87
00:02:37.529 --> 00:02:39.630
is the body telling us something isn't right.

88
00:02:40.169 --> 00:02:43.669
Our role is to notice where the young person is in that cycle

89
00:02:44.020 --> 00:02:45.389
and respond accordingly,

90
00:02:45.809 --> 00:02:47.759
not react to behavior at face value.

91
00:02:48.580 --> 00:02:50.479
But understand what's driving it,

92
00:02:50.979 --> 00:02:52.360
because when we get that right,

93
00:02:52.869 --> 00:02:54.259
we reduce escalation,

94
00:02:54.570 --> 00:02:55.720
we build trust,

95
00:02:56.059 --> 00:02:57.720
and we create emotional safety.

96
00:02:58.559 --> 00:03:00.619
And that's where real progress happens.